            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 5,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1349213687,
            "creation_date": 1349213687,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>how do these ints get declared in the first place?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>You are showing the two lines where they are declared...<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>it seems as though these values would have to be known in order for the values to be validated<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>These constants are known and these are their values.<\/p>\n\n<p>In other words, the limit for an <code>int<\/code> value is constrained by the fact that they have to fit in 32 bits. Those 2 variables are there as a convenience but are not used to determine whether an <code>int<\/code> should overflow or not.<\/p>\n\n<p>The range of <code>int<\/code> values is defined in the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-4.html#jls-4.2.1\">Java Language Specification #4.2.1<\/a> - these constants only reflect the specification:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The values of the integral types are integers in the following ranges:  <\/p>\n  \n  <ul>\n  <li>[...]<\/li>\n  <li>For int, from -2147483648 to 2147483647, inclusive<\/li>\n  <\/ul>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698696,
            "question_id": 12698544
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/qounX.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 220462,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 477878,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/477878/joachim-isaksson",
                "reputation": 181897,
                "display_name": "Joachim Isaksson"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1349213669,
            "creation_date": 1349213341,
            "body": "<p>The validations/possible overflow checks during the compilation stage are done by the compiler, which may have (and probably has) those known values hard coded. <\/p>\n\n<p>In other words, the compiler doesn't need to look at MIN_VALUE or MAX_VALUE to validate the program, those values are just treated as any constants and could as far as the compiler is concerned be defined as any value. Of course, if they were changed, your program that actually cares about the constants may not fare as well.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698612,
            "question_id": 12698544,
            "last_edit_date": 1349213669
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b31ee54d9d3789bf16fe971dbb4a2ef8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 9760,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 18157,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/18157/jim-garrison",
                "reputation": 87027,
                "display_name": "Jim Garrison",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1349213368,
            "creation_date": 1349213368,
            "body": "<p>In Java, integers are 32 bits long.  The values <code>0x07ffffff<\/code> and <code>0x08000000<\/code> are the maximum and minimum possible values, by definition.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 12698619,
            "question_id": 12698544
        }
